Executive Summary

FirstEnergy Sammis Plant

RMP Plan



Background



Energy Harbor generates electricity at the Sammis power plant in Stratton, Ohio.  In order to reduce NOx air emissions, Sammis installed a Selective Catalytic Reduction (SCR) system on units 6&7 back in 2009.  This system removes NOx by catalytically reacting NOx with Ammonia to form Nitrogen and water vapor.  The process is covered by the EPA Risk Management Program (RMP) rules due to the presence of 29 % Aqueous Ammonia.



The covered process includes:  rail car unloading, tank truck unloading, storage, and SCR feed.  There are six storage tanks that may contain up to 54,000 gallons each (90% capacity).  There is also an emergency truck unloading and feed station.



Overview of the RMP Prevention Program 

The Sammis process is considered a Program 2 site by RMP rules.  



Process protections are primarily those measures that will reduce, prevent or minimize a release from happening or, if it did happen, minimize the consequences of that threat.    These include:



Training on operations, emergencies etc;

Operators of the systems covered by the RMP plan have refresher training at least every 3 years.

Regular maintenance/SOPS;        

During deliveries, attendance by the operator is continuous until the delivery is complete;

No rail cars or tank trucks stored on site other than those in the process of being unloaded;

Onsite wireless communication;

Onsite trucks/vehicles for emergency transportation needs;   

Fire extinguishers; 

Ammonia monitors/detectors/alarms;

Main feed pump flow alarms/detector

High level tank alarms with interlock shutoffs  

Secondary containment;         

Underground vault large enough to contain the largest release and hence minimize air releases.

Storage tank design and inspections;

Temperature/pressure indicators;

Water cannon and service water hydrants (knock down Ammonia fumes);

Incident investigation procedures; 



